{"id":"1604.01286","submitter":"Elie Najm","authors":"Elie Najm and Rajai Nasser","title":"Age of Information: The Gamma Awakening","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider a scenario where a monitor is interested in being up to date with\nrespect to the status of some system which is not directly accessible to this\nmonitor. However, we assume a source node has access to the status and can send\nstatus updates as packets to the monitor through a communication system. We\nalso assume that the status updates are generated randomly as a Poisson\nprocess. The source node can manage the packet transmission to minimize the age\nof information at the destination node, which is defined as the time elapsed\nsince the last successfully transmitted update was generated at the source. We\nuse queuing theory to model the source-destination link and we assume that the\ntime to successfully transmit a packet is a gamma distributed service time. We\nconsider two packet management schemes: LCFS (Last Come First Served) with\npreemption and LCFS without preemption. We compute and analyze the average age\nand the average peak age of information under these assumptions. Moreover, we\nextend these results to the case where the service time is deterministic.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 5 Apr 2016 15:04:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-04-06"}
